At this time, we will open the remote public comment for introduction and referral calendar and I want to thank everyone for ongoing patience and cooperation as we continue to have remote public comment system.

We want remote public comment on Agendas but we reserve the right to end or limit these periods at any point if we deem the system is being abused or no longer suitable for allowing our meetings to be efficient and effective.

You can do that by going to the Website at Seattle.Gop/Counsel.

If you don't wrap up your comments, your microphone will be muted to allow me to call on the next Speaker.

Public comment period is now open.

First up is Howard Gail.
Next is Marissa.
Howard, welcome.
Good afternoon.
Howard Gail, District 7 and Commenting on failed police accountability.
We are weeks away from the one year anniversary of George Floyd nearly a year after the police unleashed violence and false arrest and gross violations of people's first amendment rights.
Upon the very people that pay them to protect and serve.
What has resulted from the many thousands of complaints about police abuse and violence?
This is a question that the Council has simply ignored or forgotten.
As of last Friday, the office of police accountable he has on only 17 complaints out of many thousands to be partially or totally sustained.
Of those complaints, 12 officers received Reprimands.
One officer received a two day suspension for pending discipline.
This along with the repeated approval of SPD murders is far more than efficient evidence that this is not working.
The accountability system has only produced more police abuse and less accountability and promises even more abuse in the months ahead.
We need to be in control of police oversight with the existing system.
We have full civilian control in places like Nashville, Oakland, Porton, Oregon and other cities.
If the Council continues to be Unmovable, this people of Seattle will take this issue back from the Council.
Thank you.
Think you.
Next up is Marissa followed by Nal Gasemi.
Hi, my name is Marissa and I am reading testimony on behalf of one of our grassroots leaders on behalf of resolution 2205.
My name is Elizabeth and I am a volunteer and grassroots leader in 2009.
At our organization, leaders are advocates for our immigrants and I am an immigrant from Mexico.
I came to the U.S. over 20 years ago.
I don't have legal status but I strive to be a good member of my community.
I volunteered at my church and my children's schools.
I am fortunate to be able to understand English which helps me navigate the system and I use this skill to help my community.
At this time, I have experienced systemic racism, discrimination and racial profiling with a lack of legal status.
I have been called illegal and have been incarcerated at the detention center for two months.
This was a time full of fear and uncertainty for myself and family because I was separated from them.
My husband and small children did not know if I could ever go back to them.
I am speaking today on behalf of all immigrants who like myself would like an opportunity to prove that they are Hard-Working and compassionate people who want to move forward in life.
People that want to feel like they belong after many years of living in the country.
Immigration reform is the right thing to do and I am grateful to the Seattle city council for their efforts and desire to take action.
Our community is at risk and now is the time to act.
Thank you.
Thank you.
Next up is Nal.
Good afternoon.
I am a board member of one America and I am providing comments to resolution 30 2005 speaking on behalf of one of our grassroots leaders.
I am a grass roots leader and also a Seattleite and proud daughter of immigrants.
The Pathway to citizenship is so important and far overdue.
Because immigrants have been facing various struggles, what would a Pathway to citizenship mean to me and my family and community?
Pathway to citizenship would put me at ease and I would lose the fear of my parents being Deported or leaving my Siblings and I behind.
It would mean them getting better opportunities to have a bigger range of jobs available and something that I hope is they can travel outside of the country and come back with ease.
I remember the first time I was away from home, it was fifth grade and we went on a school trip.
When I came home, I tugged and hugged my parents a long time because I Miss them so much.
I can't imagine being away from my parents for long.
My dad misses his mom a lot with every birthday and holiday and mother's day.
A Pathway decision ship would provide my dad and some immigrants the chance to reunite.
City Council members, thank you for understanding that our community cannot wait any longer.
We need Congress to step up.
The time to act is right now.
Thank you.
Thank you for calling in.

Hi and good afternoon.
My name is Carlos Martinez and I will read a testimony on behalf of our grassroots leader for resolution 32005.
Good afternoon city council members.
I am currently a student at Western Washington University.
I do not refer to myself exclusively as American, the U.S. has been my home since 2005.
My parents came to this country with the desire to give me a higher standard and to escape the social turmoil.
Gaining Daca status was a sigh of relief at a moment where the elected President would be ensuing so much fear into the Undocumented community, my community.
Now, I am looking into what I want to do in the future.
While my status always be in limbo?
My vision is that Congress works together to provide a Pathway to citizenship for all Undocumented individuals in this country.
We have heard enough promises but we want action.
I do appreciate the city council highlighting the urgency of this issue and I would like us to work together towards an inclusive immigration system where people like me feel safe and like we belong.
Thank you.
Thank you so much for calling today.
Next up is Roxana.
Welcome.
Thank you and hello everyone.
Good afternoon Councilmembers.
My name is Roxana and I am the deputy director at one America.
I am here today in support of resolution 32005.
Thank you to Councilmember Gonzales and all the others for your leadership on behalf of immigrant communities in sponsoring this important resolution.
One America is the largest advocacy organization in Washington state.

I personally am the daughter of immigrants from Iran who were lucky enough to come back when there was a Pathway to citizenship almost 40 years ago and there was an opportunity to rebuild our lives in the U.S.

As you have already heard from our immigrant leaders, our communities have waited way too long and immigrant communities and communities of color made immigration reform possible because we rose up in the 2020 election.
We help put Joe Biden and Kamala Harris in the White House and control of the Senate and made impacts on local and municipal level elections as well.
Yet, we see elected officials in the White House and Congress hesitate.
We have been told that we must wait and government will do the right thing but communities continue to be excluded and still continue to live in fear.
We see leaders rise to the challenge and it is time for elected officials like all of you here today to do the same.

The time is now and I am glad to see the city council acknowledging and acting on the urgency of this moment which will be a model for cities to demand immediate action to pass the Pathway of citizen ship for many people in our community.
We must work together towards a vision of an immigration system that is welcoming and inclusive and truly just.
Thank you.
Thank you for calling in today.

My name is Letty and I'm a community leader for the Washington immigrant network with more than 350 organizations working to improve conditions for immigrants in the state.
I am also the director of communities with engagement specialists serving central Washington and coordinator of the suicide prevention group.

After serving the community for more than 12 years and having a good understanding of their needs, I am encouraged to say it is important to offer immigration reform that gives dignity and respect to fellow Undocumented immigrants because they deserve it.
People that work in the field are forgotten because they are not present at these meetings.
Workers make this Nation prosperous and working long hours regardless of the weather.
We have food every day due to their effort and it is not fair that they have to live in fear due to their status.
Every time we vote, we do so in the hope that there will finally be immigration reform but that date has not arrived.
This is the right time to do it in the way to Legalize has to be provided so there can be respect and dignity.
I'm here to ask for your support and act in favor of the resolution on immigration reform.
Thank you so much.
Thank you, [speaking foreign language] and now we will move to our next Speaker who is Brenda Rodriguez followed by David Haynes.
Good afternoon Councilmembers.
I am Undocumented and ashamed.
I am with the solitary network with 350 organizations across 22 counties organizing to transform the state of Washington into a place for refugees.
I am here representing my working family who has called Washington state home for two decades.
My families have worked hard to serve this country and to feed themselves.
We have been terrorized by a constant threat of being separated.
Today is a new day and one with hope under the Haydn administration.
It is now time for accountability.
I am glad to see the Seattle city council take leadership and act on the urgency of this moment.
I also call on the city Council to step up in leadership and pass the revolution.
It is time for immigrants and families like mine to feel safe and supported.
The time is now for President Biden to fulfill his promise.
Thank you for sending this message to Congress with this resolution.
Thank you, Brenda for calling in today.

Agenda item 11 resolution 32005, a resolution urging the United States Congress to enact legislation creating a roadmap to citizenship and other legislative priorities to support immigrants and refugees.
Thank you, Madam clerk.
I moved to adopt resolution 32005.
Is there a second?
Second.
Thank you so much.
It has been moved and Seconded to adopt resolution 32005.
I am the sponsor so I will address it and then I am happy to open the floor for comments.

Before us is this important resolution that I mentioned briefly during our briefing this morning in my office has worked over the last several Ãšweeks with many community leaders including those to develop the resolution.
It is in support of community organizing efforts and representative to freedom which seeks to fix our broken immigration systems.
This resolution calls on Congress to do several things.
First, create a roadmap to citizenship for 11 million Undocumented immigrants including those residing in working here in Seattle.

To support families and through this resolution, we call on Congress to improve our standing in the eyes of the world by improving our Asylum and refugee systems and grow the numbers of refugees we admit into our country.
The city calls on our Federal Government to also put an end to private immigration detention just like our Washington state legislator did.
We must have a moratorium on deportation.
Finally, we asked Congress to not leave out immigrants and especially Thse that are Undocumented of any pandemic recovery efforts because of their status.
It is vital that Congress acts with urgency and uses every tool at their disposal including budget reconciliation to finally achieve comprehensive immigration reform.
As a Councilmember, I have heard so many stories over the last 15 months about how that pandemic has exacerbated and magnified what we have in our society.
This is con's for so many during the pandemic and has been devastating.
Thousands of local families were left out of relief and assistance needed to survive this pandemic because of their immigration status.
Many and augmented immigrants cannot access my fines like unemployment insurance and other types of benefits that they need in order to continue t survive.

Local governments like Seattle have continued to step up as both the first and last line of defense and I am proud of the work our city has done to support our neighbors including making sure that we were not excluding our Undocumented neighbors from our very own Jumpstart Seattle payroll tax.
We do not have the resources to meet the scale of our community members.
We need our Federal Government to act once and for all and with urgency.
That must ensure immigrant communities do not get left behind as they come out of the pandemic.

After four years of the Federal Government that has continually targeted immigrants and refugees telling us we do not belong in Verbalizing our communities and neighborhoods with Phobia and racism and family separation.

It is time for reckoning and healing and it is my deep hope that Congress will finally Act and not delay any longer, passing this resolution is absolutely necessary in order for our representatives to have all of the resources and all the tools and support of the local jurisdiction and constituents to go to Washington D.C. and advocate accordingly.
With that, I would encourage and appreciate your Yes vote on this resolution.
